dom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Atte","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Muslim (mainly Pakistan and Egypt): variant of   Ata  .","West African (Ghana): from an Akan (Fante) male personal name denoting a twin. Compare   Arthur  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ata","meanings":["Turkish: ornamental name, nickname, or relationship name from <i>ata</i> ‘father, elder’.","Muslim (mainly Egypt): from a personal name based on Arabic <i>ʿaṭā</i> ‘gift’ (understood as ‘gift from God’). Compare   Atallah   and   Atta  ."]}]},{"name":"Wode","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: unexplained."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Wyckhurst Atte Wode was born about 1224, his father, Peter Piers De Wyckhurst Sr., was 31 and his mother, Mrs. Alice Wyckhurst, was 25. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Julia De Avenell. He died in 1278, in Coulsdon, Surrey, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 55, and was buried in Coulsdon, London, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1224–1278":"umbes 1224–1278","1224–1278":"1224–1278","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","1224–Female":"1224–Surn